            <p>1906 Indiana Av.<lb/>
                Chicago Ill. Oct. 12<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1890.<lb/></p>
            <p>The Rev. S. Morais&#44; LL. D. Philadelphia&#44; Pa.<lb/>
                Rev. and Venerated Sir&#45;&#45;<lb/></p>
            <p>The Board of Directors of the Jewish Training School of<lb/> Chicago&#44; knowing the deep interest you take in whatever affects the wel&#45;<lb/>fare of the Jewish Russian immigrants do themselves the honor to<lb/> inform you that the dedication of the School&#45;house&#44; erected recently at a cost of<lb/> &#36;60&#44;000&#44; will take place on Sunday Oct. 19th. and to extend to you a most<lb/> cordial invitation to grace the exercises by your presence.  In case<lb/> your personal attendance is rendered impossible&#44; a few words from you<lb/> conveying to us your encouragement&#44; to be read on the occasion&#44; would be<lb/> highly appreciated.  It is our aim to instil into the hearts of our<lb/> pupils&#45;&#45;the children of our poor Refugees&#45;&#45;through a most complete<lb/> training of both head and <hi rend="underline">hand</hi>&#44; a love for manual labor and<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>thus lead them to embrace the avocations of honest<lb/> and honored artisans&#44; for which we shall endeavor to<lb/> prepare them.  Your sympathy will be of great benefit<lb/> to us.  We need scarcely assure you&#44; that nothing will<lb/> be done to violate the religious convictions or interfere<lb/> with the religious freedom of our words.  Looking<lb/> forward with confidence to the receipt of your message<lb/> of cheer&#44; I embrace this grateful opportunity to<lb/> add to the sentiments of regards of the Board<lb/> the assurance of my highest esteem&#44; and<lb/> remain&#44; Rev Sir&#44; yours most respectfully<lb/> Emil G Hirsch<lb/> Chairman of the Comm. on<lb/> School.<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
